text: Recording studio nerd here... That audio improvement comparison you did at around 3mins was an 'aural exciter' that makes audio sound better when it is super simple and single channel but entirely destroys sound quality when it is more complex. These types of sound effects are so awful that most professional bands on tour in their rider/contract state that no 'exciters' are allowed in the signal path on any channel because when it comes to mixing live sound an exciter will destroy sound quality. In other words TV makers are not to be trusted with sound quality, only fake  sound quality. Get some good recording studio reference speakers and some amps and bypass all audio features on your TV other than Audio out.

I've since bought a Sony, updated my home network to include regular vulnerability scanning of all Internet of Things (IoT) devices on the network, and considering VLANning some of these things to stop potential attacks from devices that could potentially be compromised thanks to fewer/no further firmware updates from their manufacturers.  This TV will look good for a couple of years, but eventually, it'll be a big dumb beast long before it should be.  Also: don't get me started on HDMI 2.1/2.1a specs.
